74":"about 0974","994":"0994","1025":"1025","1035":"1035","1013":"1013","1067":"1067","Beauvais-Nord-Ouest, Beauvais, Oise, Picardie, France":"Beauvais, Oise, Picardie, France","England":"England","Clermont, Clermont, Oise, Picardie, France":"Clermont, Oise, Picardie, France","Clermont, Oise, Picardie, France":"Clermont, Oise, Picardie, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Marguerite","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Margaret  , also used in the English-speaking world, where its use has been reinforced by the fact that the name was adopted in the 19th century for a garden flower, a large cultivated variety of daisy. <i>Margaret</i> was earlier used in English as a dialect word denoting the ox-eye daisy, and the French equivalent was borrowed into English just in time to catch the vogue for deriving girls' names from vocabulary words denoting flowers.  See also  Daisy ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705176,"age":6,"year":"0980","julianDay":2078998,"title":"Vikings Invade England","description":"Viking raiders from Scandinavia invaded England in 980. Years later in 991, the English government paid them 10,000 in hopes for peace. The Viking raiders, however, continued to force more money from England.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705177,"age":20,"year":"0994","julianDay":2084112,"title":"Danes Attack London","description":"Danes and Norwegians attacked London unsuccessfully in 994.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anglo-Saxon_London#10th_century_London","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Anglo-Saxon London","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705179,"age":39,"year":"1013","julianDay":2091051,"title":"Sweyn Forkbeard","description":"The Danes raided and captured England. Sweyn, King of Danes, was declared King of England on Christmas Day.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sweyn_Forkbeard","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Sweyn Forkbeard","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705180,"age":42,"year":"1016","julianDay":2092146,"title":"Canut the Great","description":"As Aethelred, King of England died, his son, Edmund Ironside devised a truce with Danish King Canute. The truce divided the kingdom between the two but Edmund died shortly after and became King of England. Several years later, he also became king of Denmark.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cnut_the_Great","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Cnut the Great","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705181,"age":61,"year":"1035","julianDay":2099086,"title":"England Divided","description":"King Canute died in 1035 and England was divided between his three sons. His son Sweyn received Norway, Harthacanute received Denmark, and Harold Harefoot received North England.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705182,"age":92,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705183,"age":112,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Marguerite de Ramerupt was born about 0974, in England. She had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter with Hugues De Creil et de Mouchy."},"et":{"about 0974–":"umbes 0974–Surnud","0996–1060":"0996–1060","1010–1098":"1010–1098","1025–1049":"1025–1049","1025–1067":"1025–1067","1030–Male":"1030–Surnud","0974–Female":"0974–Surnud","about 1030":"umbes 1030","1066":"1066","1010":"1010","1098":"1098","1086":"1086","1030":"1030","1060":"1060","0974":"0974","0996":"0996","980":"0980","1016":"1016","1049":"1049","about 0974":"umbes 0974","994":"0994","1025":"1025","1035":"1035","1013":"1013","1067":"1067","Beauvais-Nord-Ouest, Beauvais, Oise, Picardie, France":"Beauvais, Oise, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","England":"England","Clermont, Clermont, Oise, Picardie, France":"Clermont, Oise, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Clermont, Oise, Picardie, France":"Clermont, Oise, Picardie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 0974–":"noin 0974–Kuollut","0996–1060":"0996–1060","1010–1098":"1010–1098","1025–1049":"1025–1049","1025–1067":"1025–1067","1030–Male":"1030–Kuollut","0974–Female":"0974–Kuollut","about 1030":"noin 1030","1066":"1066","1010":"1010","1098":"1098","1086":"1086","1030":"1030","1060":"1060","0974":"0974","0996":"0996","980":"0980","1016":"1016","1049":"1049","about 0974":"noin 0974","994":"0994","1025":"1025","1035":"1035","1013":"1013","1067":"1067","Beauvais-Nord-Ouest, Beauvais, Oise, Picardie, France":"Beauvais, Oise, Picardie, Ranska","England":"England","Clermont, Clermont, Oise, Picardie, France":"Clermont, Oise, Picardie, Ranska","Cler